# Service Conventions

## There Is No Service Layer

Rails does not have a service layer. Business logic belongs on the model. If you are reaching for `app/services/`, stop and ask where this logic *actually* lives.

```ruby
# Good — domain verb on the model
class Article < ApplicationRecord
  def publish(by: Current.user)
    transaction do
      create_publication!(publisher: by)
      update!(published_at: Time.current)
    end
  end
end

# Bad — service wrapping a model call
class PublishArticleService
  def call(article, user:)
    article.update!(published: true, published_by: user)
  end
end
```

## Where Logic Actually Lives

| Situation | Where It Goes |
|-----------|---------------|
| Operates on a single model instance | Model method (domain verb) |
| Shared behaviour across models | Concern |
| Complex multi-step operation on one aggregate | PORO namespaced under the model |
| Multi-field form spanning models or workflow | Form object (`ActiveModel::Model`) |
| Async work, retries, scheduling | Job (`ActiveJob`) |
| Incoming email processing | Mailbox (`ActionMailbox`) |
| Sending email | Mailer (`ActionMailer`) |
| External API integration | PORO in `app/models/` namespaced under a domain noun |
| Controller coordinates two models | Inline controller orchestration — no wrapper needed |

## POROs Under Model Namespaces

When a model method grows too complex or an operation involves several steps within a single aggregate, extract to a PORO namespaced under the primary model. These live in `app/models/`, not `app/services/`.

```ruby
# app/models/account/onboarding.rb
class Account::Onboarding
  def initialize(account)
    @account = account
  end

  def complete(params)
    @account.transaction do
      @account.update!(params.slice(:name, :plan))
      @account.memberships.create!(user: Current.user, role: :owner)
      @account.create_default_project!
    end
  end
end
```

## Form Objects for Multi-Model Writes

When a single form creates or updates records across multiple models, use a form object with `ActiveModel::Model`. This replaces both `accepts_nested_attributes_for` and service objects.

```ruby
# app/models/registration.rb
class Registration
  include ActiveModel::Model
  include ActiveModel::Attributes

  attribute :name, :string
  attribute :email, :string
  attribute :company_name, :string

  validates :name, :email, :company_name, presence: true

  def save
    return false unless valid?

    Account.transaction do
      account = Account.create!(name: company_name)
      User.create!(name: name, email: email, account: account)
    end
  end
end
```

## Jobs Are Your Async Service Layer

Anything that should happen in the background is a job, not a service. The model enqueues, the job executes.

```ruby
# Model enqueues
after_create_commit :send_welcome_later

private
  def send_welcome_later
    WelcomeMailer.with(user: self).welcome.deliver_later
  end
```

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| `app/services/` directory | Model methods, POROs under models, form objects, jobs |
| Single-method `call` service objects | Model method |
| Service wrapping one `update!` | Model domain verb |
| Service as a "transaction script" | Model method with `transaction` block |
| Service objects injecting models to simulate loose coupling | If you need the model, be the model or live under it — PORO constructor injection is fine; injection-as-architectural-boundary is not |
| `ApplicationService` base class | No base class needed — each PORO stands alone |
| Service for form validation | Form object (`ActiveModel::Model`) |
| Service for async work | Job (`ActiveJob`) |
| Service for email | Mailer (`ActionMailer`) |
| Generic `execute`, `run` method names on POROs and form objects | Domain verbs: `complete`, `process`, `import`. Exception: `perform` is the ActiveJob contract and must not be renamed. |
